dspace-development.title: Update the X.509 certificates for the Symplectic Elements servers

comments.body:
These were successfully updated, although there were significant issues in transferring the files to the server. The following needed to be performed to convert and transfer the certificate files:

```bash
openssl pkcs12 -export -out oaworkflow_dev_princeton_edu_cert.pfx -inkey oaworkflow_dev_princeton_edu_cert.key -in oaworkflow_dev_princeton_edu_cert.cer
hexdump -e'16/1 " %03u "' oaworkflow_dev_princeton_edu_cert.pfx > oaworkflow_dev_princeton_edu_cert.pfx.bin
```

The binary output of `hexdump` was then copied to the PowerShell with the following:
```pwsh
New-Item -ItemType file .\oaworkflow_dev_princeton_edu_cert.pfx.bin
'' | Out-File .\oaworkflow_dev_princeton_edu_cert.pfx.bin
psEdit .\oaworkflow_dev_princeton_edu_cert.pfx.bin

[string]$hex = Get-Content -Path oaworkflow_dev_princeton_edu_cert.pfx.bin
[Byte[]] $temp = $hex -split ' '
[System.IO.File]::WriteAllBytes("oaworkflow_dev_princeton_edu_cert.pfx", $temp)
```

One is then able to upload the X.509 certificates using the following interface:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1443986/101311050-82d36b00-381e-11eb-959a-5cf2a2e1f2cf.png)

There are currently issues affecting clients attempting to connect to the server:
```
> openssl s_client -connect oaworkflow.princeton.edu:443                                                              % rb 2.6.5 09:03:09
CONNECTED(00000005)
write:errno=54
---
no peer certificate available
---
No client certificate CA names sent
---
SSL handshake has read 0 bytes and written 0 bytes
---
New, (NONE), Cipher is (NONE)
Secure Renegotiation IS NOT supported
Compression: NONE
Expansion: NONE
No ALPN negotiated
SSL-Session:
    Protocol  : TLSv1.2
    Cipher    : 0000
    Session-ID:
    Session-ID-ctx:
    Master-Key:
    Start Time: 1607350218
    Timeout   : 7200 (sec)
    Verify return code: 0 (ok)
---
```

I have now found that I can no longer access the the production Windows VM (this was after several reboots), and I have created https://princeton.service-now.com/service?sys_id=ce6136331bf82010435885d56b4bcb11&view=sp&id=ticket&table=incident in response to this.

I can still access the `dev` Windows VM, and will proceed working to resolve the errors in this environment.

I have located the solution and repaired this for the `dev` environment (I needed to manually reset the `Site Bindings` entry for the Elements application:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1443986/101369177-feacd200-3875-11eb-862b-a8bd358f66ef.png)

After resolving https://princeton.service-now.com/service?sys_id=ce6136331bf82010435885d56b4bcb11&view=sp&id=ticket&table=incident by following the recommended steps on https://becomethesolution.com/an-authentication-error-has-occurred-code-0x80004005-remote-desktop, I was again able to access the Windows VM and restore service to Elements on the IIS.

dspace-development.title: DataSpace Bitstreams for certain Items cannot be downloaded

comments.body: This Item is specified as having been accessioned on 2016-08-09, and the "File" (presumably the Bitstream title) is rendered as `null`.
The database records do not yield any metadata for the related Bitstreams and Bundles with NULL values.
https://git.atmire.com/clients/princeton-5/-/blob/dataspace-client-DEV/dspace-jspui/src/main/java/org/dspace/app/webui/jsptag/ItemTag.java#L976 is where the Bitstream title is not being rendered.

I could not diagnose precisely why this was occurring (perhaps the caching in https://git.atmire.com/clients/princeton-5/-/blob/dataspace-client-DEV/dspace-api/src/main/java/org/dspace/content/DSpaceObject.java#L1249 is problematic? I have seen this trigger anomalies once before). However, editing the Bitstream metadata using the Item Edit Form looks to be the solution.
This was fixed in the production environment, and shared with the reporting user for feedback.

marc_liberation.title: Finalize indexing infrastructure
Calculate the catalog_date field when indexing a single record
Use lando for postgres
Update catalog_date field in traject for Alma records

comments.body:
- [ ] **Single Records** https://github.com/pulibrary/marc_liberation/issues/925
refs https://github.com/pulibrary/marc_liberation/issues/748

1. Get a single alma record with `p_avail` and `e_avail` parameters: https://developers.exlibrisgroup.com/console/?url=/wp-content/uploads/alma/openapi/bibs.json#/Catalog/get%2Falmaws%2Fv1%2Fbibs%2F%7Bmms_id%7D

2. If it has any `AVA` fields that correspond to `p_avail` (physical availability), get the list of items to get the `<creation_date>` . Get the earliest `creation_date` from the <items> list.

3. If there are no `AVA` fields that correspond to `p_avail`, look for `AVE` fields that correspond to `e_avail`. Each `AVE` field has a portfolio id included. For each `AVE` field in the API response, you must retrieve the portfolio information. Use the oldest `<portfolio><activation_date>` from the attached portfolios. See https://developers.exlibrisgroup.com/alma/apis/docs/xsd/rest_portfolio.xsd/

4. If there is no `p_avail` or `e_avail`, use `<bib><created_date>`.

- [ ] **Publishing profiles** https://github.com/pulibrary/marc_liberation/issues/926

Bibliographic Enrichment -> Create date subfield 950b
Physical Items Enrichment -> Create date subfield 876d
Electronic Inventory Enrichment -> Activation date subfield 951w

1. Similar to the Single Record if there is a `876` field don't use the `951` fields. 
2. If there are no `876` or `951` then use the bib create date: Bibliographic Enrichment `950b`.

comments.body: @hackartisan This is something that @mzelesky wanted to review. @mzelesky or I will update the issue when there is a definite answer.

> @christinach This issue says `852` but the comment in the file says `952` -- can you clarify?

The `952 | b` and `952 | c` can be disregarded because we updated the publishing profile to put the 852 fields from the holdings in the records. 
Since bib records can have other 852 fields, we need to skip any 852 fields that do not have subfield 8 with a value that begins with 22 (prefix identifies as a holding record) and ends with the institution suffix (5 digits, currently 06421).

example:
```
852 0  $0 4148329 $b f $h HC1000 $i .O48 2001 
902    $a nv $b m $6 a $7 m $d v $f 1 $e 20050908 
904    $a nbs $b a $h n $c b $e 20030213 
950    $c 2020-07-23 14:45:06 US/Eastern $b 2020-05-27 16:32:31 US/Eastern $a false 
852 0  $b MAIN $c main $h HC1000 $i .O48 2001 $8 2281654580006421 
952    $d 2020-05-27 20:32:54 $8 2281654580006421 $a 2020-05-27 20:32:54 $b Main Library $c Stacks $e false 
876    $0 2281654580006421 $a 2381654560006421 $j 1 $i 0 $d 2020-05-27 20:32:54 $h HC1000 .O48 2001 $p 32101046019913
```
first 852 should be skipped because there is no subfield 8.

pulfalight.title: Search term highlighting is not working on the site-wide search

comments.body:
+1 on questions 1, 2, imo.

Re: question #3: 
The container indicator gets overwritten, so that seems pretty final unless we store the old indicator in a note field. The only place I can see atm is in container_locations[note]. It would be a bit of a hack, but it would give us a failsafe.

The indicator aside, the workflow for re-doing a container would be something like "starting at the first barcode I had scanned, going for n sequential barcodes, do something." The 'something' can be change the location or the profile, or even the barcode I guess.

One note about how ASpace validates barcodes--it mostly doesn't (any characters, any length are allowed), with one exception: it doesn't allow duplicate barcodes (they will return an http "bad request").
Ah, I didn't think about ASpace errors. If ASpace errors in the middle, should I be able to hit the button again?

@faithc provided me with the current AbID documentation for processors (https://docs.google.com/document/d/17nML-1ZRG_Kd-rKi6F2OXpIWEYem5sedXI9okPfe3Ao/edit), which has the following note about undoing errors. That workflow works because the Access DB stores all records it created.

```HOW TO DELETE RECORDS:
*If you realize belatedly that you made a mistake after you’ve clicked “Output All” but before you’ve closed the UserAll 
form, you can return to the UserAll form and click “Undo today’s output” at the top of the form. The original box numbers, 
which display in italics following export, will become un-italicized after you’ve undone the output. In order to actually delete 
any items, you still need to click “Delete” next to individual rows to delete single items. When you have corrected your 
mistakes, you can output again by clicking “Output All.”
*If you realize belatedly that you made a mistake after you’ve closed out of the database entirely, go to the Start form and 
click “Recent Activity.” When prompted to “Enter the number of days to review,” enter a number below 1000 depending on 
how long ago you created the records you want to delete. Once the UserAllRecentActivity form opens, click “Undo output.” 
You should see a list of all items you have created within that time period. Then click the “Delete” button next to each 
individual record you want to delete. When you are finished, click “Output All” to re-do the output of any records in the list 
you do want to keep.
NOTE ABOUT ERRORS: Minor errors in records, i.e. those not relating to barcodes or their associated AbIDs, such as wrong 
collection codes or traditional box numbers, can be corrected in the XML export file rather than deleting and recreating 
records in the database as the database is not meant to serve as the master record for the data it creates.
```

> Ah, I didn't think about ASpace errors. If ASpace errors in the middle, should I be able to hit the button again?

Yes, I would think so

PROBLEM: Don Thornbury just alerted me to the fact that the AbID db is also used by catalogers / non-archivists, for data that does not live in ASpace. (They use MacroExpress to add it to Voyager). That means the current implementation plan doesn't work, since it relies on ASpace to know what the next available number in the sequence is. 

Essentially, to maintain that functionality, we need a freestanding db that both generates and stores the AbIDs (or the last available for each profile, anyway), and then EITHER overwrites the ASpace record OR outputs the AbID's as XML (or sends them to Alma, later).

(In light of this, I wonder whether it's easier to just keep the current Access db, and just add functionality to import its XML output into ASpace.)

From Kevin on Slack:
`I think we could support it in the context of the libjobs if we agree to take on the responsibility of persisting the IDs.`

We probably wouldn't have to persist all AbID's--just the last one for each super-location (Firestone, Mudd) + profile. And at the end of each bulk update operation, we'd have to overwrite that value for next time.
